52 // Properties of a value that are tracked by the propagation. ----
53 // A property that is marked as present (i.e. bit is set) dentes that the ----
54 // value is known (proven) to have this property. Not all combinations ----
55 // of bits make sense, for example Zero and NonZero are mutually exclusive, ----
56 // but on the other hand, Zero implies Finite. In this case, whenever ----
57 // the Zero property is present, Finite should also be present. ----
58 class ConstantProperties { ----
59 public: ----
60 enum { ----
61 Unknown = 0x0000, ----
62 Zero = 0x0001, ----
63 NonZero = 0x0002, ----
64 Finite = 0x0004, ----
65 Infinity = 0x0008, ----
66 NaN = 0x0010, ----
67 SignedZero = 0x0020, ----
68 NumericProperties = (Zero|NonZero|Finite|Infinity|NaN|SignedZero), ----
69 PosOrZero = 0x0100, ----
70 NegOrZero = 0x0200, ----
71 SignProperties = (PosOrZero|NegOrZero), ----
72 Everything = (NumericProperties|SignProperties) ----
73 }; ----
74 ----
75 // For a given constant, deduce the set of trackable properties that this ----
76 // constant has. ----
77 static uint32_t deduce(const Constant *C); ----
78 }; ----

96 ----

102 // Lattice cell, based on that was described in the W-Z paper on constant ----
103 // propagation. ----
104 // Latice cell will be allowed to hold multiple constant values. While ----
105 // multiple values would normally indicate "bottom", we can still derive ----
106 // some useful information from them. For example, comparison X > 0 ----
107 // could be folded if all the values in the cell associated with X are ----
108 // positive. ----
109 class LatticeCell { ----
110 private: ----
111 enum { Normal, Top, Bottom }; ----
112 ----
113 static const unsigned MaxCellSize = 4; ----
114 ----
115 unsigned Kind:2; ----
116 unsigned Size:3; ----
117 unsigned IsSpecial:1; ----
118 unsigned :0; ----
119 ----
120 public: ----
121 union { ----
122 uint32_t Properties; ----
123 const Constant *Value; ----
124 const Constant *Values[MaxCellSize]; ----
125 }; ----
126 ----
127 LatticeCell() : Kind(Top), Size(0), IsSpecial(false) { 0
128 for (const Constant *&Value : Values) 0
129 Value = nullptr; 0
130 } 0
131 ----
132 bool meet(const LatticeCell &L); ----
133 bool add(const Constant *C); ----
134 bool add(uint32_t Property); ----
135 uint32_t properties() const; ----
136 unsigned size() const { return Size; } 0
137 ----
138 LatticeCell(const LatticeCell &L) { 0
139 // This memcpy also copies Properties (when L.Size == 0). ----
140 uint32_t N = 0
141 L.IsSpecial ? sizeof L.Properties : L.Size * sizeof(const Constant *); 0
142 memcpy(Values, L.Values, N); 0
143 Kind = L.Kind; 0
144 Size = L.Size; 0
145 IsSpecial = L.IsSpecial; 0
146 } 0
147 ----
148 LatticeCell &operator=(const LatticeCell &L) { 0
149 if (this != &L) { 0
150 // This memcpy also copies Properties (when L.Size == 0). ----
151 uint32_t N = L.IsSpecial ? sizeof L.Properties 0
152 : L.Size * sizeof(const Constant *); 0
153 memcpy(Values, L.Values, N); 0
154 Kind = L.Kind; 0
155 Size = L.Size; 0
156 IsSpecial = L.IsSpecial; 0
157 } ----
158 return *this; 0
159 } ----
160 ----
161 bool isSingle() const { return size() == 1; } 0
162 bool isProperty() const { return IsSpecial; } 0
163 bool isTop() const { return Kind == Top; } 0
164 bool isBottom() const { return Kind == Bottom; } 0
165 ----
166 bool setBottom() { 0
167 bool Changed = (Kind != Bottom); 0
168 Kind = Bottom; 0
169 Size = 0; 0
170 IsSpecial = false; 0
171 return Changed; 0
172 } ----
173 ----
174 void print(raw_ostream &os) const; ----
175 ----
176 private: ----
177 void setProperty() { 0
178 IsSpecial = true; 0
179 Size = 0; 0
180 Kind = Normal; 0
181 } 0
182 ----
183 bool convertToProperty(); ----
184 }; ----

201 // Mapping: vreg -> cell ----
202 // The keys are registers _without_ subregisters. This won't allow ----
203 // definitions in the form of "vreg:subreg = ...". Such definitions ----
204 // would be questionable from the point of view of SSA, since the "vreg" ----
205 // could not be initialized in its entirety (specifically, an instruction ----
206 // defining the "other part" of "vreg" would also count as a definition ----
207 // of "vreg", which would violate the SSA). ----
208 // If a value of a pair vreg:subreg needs to be obtained, the cell for ----
209 // "vreg" needs to be looked up, and then the value of subregister "subreg" ----
210 // needs to be evaluated. ----
211 class CellMap { ----
212 public: ----
213 CellMap() { 0
214 assert(Top.isTop()); 0
215 Bottom.setBottom(); 0
216 } 0
217 ----
218 void clear() { Map.clear(); } 0
219 ----
220 bool has(Register R) const { 0
221 // All non-virtual registers are considered "bottom". ----
222 if (!R.isVirtual()) 0
223 return true; 0
224 MapType::const_iterator F = Map.find(R); 0
225 return F != Map.end(); 0
226 } ----
227 ----
228 const LatticeCell &get(Register R) const { 0
229 if (!R.isVirtual()) 0
230 return Bottom; 0
231 MapType::const_iterator F = Map.find(R); 0
232 if (F != Map.end()) 0
233 return F->second; 0
234 return Top; 0
235 } ----
236 ----
237 // Invalidates any const references. ----
238 void update(Register R, const LatticeCell &L) { Map[R] = L; } 0
239 ----
240 void print(raw_ostream &os, const TargetRegisterInfo &TRI) const; ----
241 ----
242 private: ----
243 using MapType = std::map; ----
244 ----
245 MapType Map; ----
246 // To avoid creating "top" entries, return a const reference to ----
247 // this cell in "get". Also, have a "Bottom" cell to return from ----
248 // get when a value of a physical register is requested. ----
249 LatticeCell Top, Bottom; ----
250 ----
251 public: ----
252 using const_iterator = MapType::const_iterator; ----
253 ----
254 const_iterator begin() const { return Map.begin(); } 0
255 const_iterator end() const { return Map.end(); } 0
256 }; ----
257 ----
258 bool run(MachineFunction &MF); ----
259 ----
260 private: ----
261 void visitPHI(const MachineInstr &PN); ----
262 void visitNonBranch(const MachineInstr &MI); ----
263 void visitBranchesFrom(const MachineInstr &BrI); ----
264 void visitUsesOf(unsigned R); ----
265 bool computeBlockSuccessors(const MachineBasicBlock *MB, ----
266 SetVector &Targets); ----

287 // The "evaluator/rewriter" of machine instructions. This is an abstract ----
288 // base class that provides the interface that the propagator will use, ----
289 // as well as some helper functions that are target-independent. ----
290 class MachineConstEvaluator { ----
291 public: ----
292 MachineConstEvaluator(MachineFunction &Fn) 0
293 : TRI(*Fn.getSubtarget().getRegisterInfo()), 0
294 MF(Fn), CX(Fn.getFunction().getContext()) {} 0
295 virtual ~MachineConstEvaluator() = default; 0
296 ----
297 // The required interface: ----
298 // - A set of three "evaluate" functions. Each returns "true" if the ----
299 // computation succeeded, "false" otherwise. ----
300 // (1) Given an instruction MI, and the map with input values "Inputs", ----
301 // compute the set of output values "Outputs". An example of when ----
302 // the computation can "fail" is if MI is not an instruction that ----
303 // is recognized by the evaluator. ----
304 // (2) Given a register R (as reg:subreg), compute the cell that ----
305 // corresponds to the "subreg" part of the given register. ----
306 // (3) Given a branch instruction BrI, compute the set of target blocks. ----
307 // If the branch can fall-through, add null (0) to the list of ----
308 // possible targets. ----
309 // - A function "rewrite", that given the cell map after propagation, ----
310 // could rewrite instruction MI in a more beneficial form. Return ----
311 // "true" if a change has been made, "false" otherwise. ----
312 using CellMap = MachineConstPropagator::CellMap; ----
313 virtual bool evaluate(const MachineInstr &MI, const CellMap &Inputs, ----
314 CellMap &Outputs) = 0; ----
315 virtual bool evaluate(const RegisterSubReg &R, const LatticeCell &SrcC, ----
316 LatticeCell &Result) = 0; ----
317 virtual bool evaluate(const MachineInstr &BrI, const CellMap &Inputs, ----
318 SetVector &Targets, ----
319 bool &CanFallThru) = 0; ----
320 virtual bool rewrite(MachineInstr &MI, const CellMap &Inputs) = 0; ----
321 ----
322 const TargetRegisterInfo &TRI; ----
323 ----
324 protected: ----
325 MachineFunction &MF; ----
326 LLVMContext &CX; ----

328 struct Comparison { ----
329 enum { ----
330 Unk = 0x00, ----
331 EQ = 0x01, ----
332 NE = 0x02, ----
333 L = 0x04, // Less-than property. ----
334 G = 0x08, // Greater-than property. ----
335 U = 0x40, // Unsigned property. ----
336 LTs = L, ----
337 LEs = L | EQ, ----
338 GTs = G, ----
339 GEs = G | EQ, ----
340 LTu = L | U, ----
341 LEu = L | EQ | U, ----
342 GTu = G | U, ----
343 GEu = G | EQ | U ----
344 }; ----
345 ----
346 static uint32_t negate(uint32_t Cmp) { 0
347 if (Cmp == EQ) 0
348 return NE; 0
349 if (Cmp == NE) 0
350 return EQ; 0
351 assert((Cmp & (L|G)) != (L|G)); 0
352 return Cmp ^ (L|G); 0
353 } ----
354 }; ----

429 uint32_t ConstantProperties::deduce(const Constant *C) { 0
430 if (isa(C)) { 0
431 const ConstantInt *CI = cast(C); 0
432 if (CI->isZero()) 0
433 return Zero | PosOrZero | NegOrZero | Finite; 0
434 uint32_t Props = (NonZero | Finite); 0
435 if (CI->isNegative()) 0
436 return Props | NegOrZero; 0
437 return Props | PosOrZero; 0
438 } ----
439 ----
440 if (isa(C)) { 0
441 const ConstantFP *CF = cast(C); 0
442 uint32_t Props = CF->isNegative() ? (NegOrZero|NonZero) 0
443 : PosOrZero; 0
444 if (CF->isZero()) 0
445 return (Props & ~NumericProperties) | (Zero|Finite); 0
446 Props = (Props & ~NumericProperties) | NonZero; 0
447 if (CF->isNaN()) 0
448 return (Props & ~NumericProperties) | NaN; 0
449 const APFloat &Val = CF->getValueAPF(); 0
450 if (Val.isInfinity()) 0
451 return (Props & ~NumericProperties) | Infinity; 0
452 Props |= Finite; 0
453 return Props; 0
454 } ----
455 ----
456 return Unknown; 0
457 } ----

459 // Convert a cell from a set of specific values to a cell that tracks ----
460 // properties. ----
461 bool LatticeCell::convertToProperty() { 0
462 if (isProperty()) 0
463 return false; 0
464 // Corner case: converting a fresh (top) cell to "special". ----
465 // This can happen, when adding a property to a top cell. ----
466 uint32_t Everything = ConstantProperties::Everything; 0
467 uint32_t Ps = !isTop() ? properties() 0
468 : Everything; 0
469 if (Ps != ConstantProperties::Unknown) { 0
470 Properties = Ps; 0
471 setProperty(); 0
472 } else { ----
473 setBottom(); 0
474 } ----
475 return true; 0
476 } ----

478 #ifndef NDEBUG ----
479 void LatticeCell::print(raw_ostream &os) const { 0
480 if (isProperty()) { 0
481 os << "{ "; 0
482 uint32_t Ps = properties(); 0
483 if (Ps & ConstantProperties::Zero) 0
484 os << "zero "; 0
485 if (Ps & ConstantProperties::NonZero) 0
486 os << "nonzero "; 0
487 if (Ps & ConstantProperties::Finite) 0
488 os << "finite "; 0
489 if (Ps & ConstantProperties::Infinity) 0
490 os << "infinity "; 0
491 if (Ps & ConstantProperties::NaN) 0
492 os << "nan "; 0
493 if (Ps & ConstantProperties::PosOrZero) 0
494 os << "poz "; 0
495 if (Ps & ConstantProperties::NegOrZero) 0
496 os << "nez "; 0
497 os << '}'; 0
498 return; 0
499 } ----
500 ----
501 os << "{ "; 0
502 if (isBottom()) { 0
503 os << "bottom"; 0
504 } else if (isTop()) { 0
505 os << "top"; 0
506 } else { ----
507 for (unsigned i = 0; i < size(); ++i) { 0
508 const Constant *C = Values[i]; 0
509 if (i != 0) 0
510 os << ", "; 0
511 C->print(os); 0
512 } ----
513 } ----
514 os << " }"; 0
515 } ----
516 #endif ----

518 // "Meet" operation on two cells. This is the key of the propagation ----
519 // algorithm. ----
520 bool LatticeCell::meet(const LatticeCell &L) { 0
521 bool Changed = false; 0
522 if (L.isBottom()) 0
523 Changed = setBottom(); 0
524 if (isBottom() || L.isTop()) 0
525 return Changed; 0
526 if (isTop()) { 0
527 *this = L; 0
528 // L can be neither Top nor Bottom, so *this must have changed. ----
529 return true; 0
530 } ----
531 ----
532 // Top/bottom cases covered. Need to integrate L's set into ours. ----
533 if (L.isProperty()) 0
534 return add(L.properties()); 0
535 for (unsigned i = 0; i < L.size(); ++i) { 0
536 const Constant *LC = L.Values[i]; 0
537 Changed |= add(LC); 0
538 } ----
539 return Changed; 0
540 } ----
541 ----
542 // Add a new constant to the cell. This is actually where the cell update ----
543 // happens. If a cell has room for more constants, the new constant is added. ----
544 // Otherwise, the cell is converted to a "property" cell (i.e. a cell that ----
545 // will track properties of the associated values, and not the values ----
546 // themselves. Care is taken to handle special cases, like "bottom", etc. ----
547 bool LatticeCell::add(const Constant *LC) { 0
548 assert(LC); 0
549 if (isBottom()) 0
550 return false; 0
551 ----
552 if (!isProperty()) { 0
553 // Cell is not special. Try to add the constant here first, ----
554 // if there is room. ----
555 unsigned Index = 0; 0
556 while (Index < Size) { 0
557 const Constant *C = Values[Index]; 0
558 // If the constant is already here, no change is needed. ----
559 if (C == LC) 0
560 return false; 0
561 Index++; 0
562 } ----
563 if (Index < MaxCellSize) { 0
564 Values[Index] = LC; 0
565 Kind = Normal; 0
566 Size++; 0
567 return true; 0
568 } ----
569 } ----
570 ----
571 bool Changed = false; 0
572 ----
573 // This cell is special, or is not special, but is full. After this ----
574 // it will be special. ----
575 Changed = convertToProperty(); 0
576 uint32_t Ps = properties(); 0
577 uint32_t NewPs = Ps & ConstantProperties::deduce(LC); 0
578 if (NewPs == ConstantProperties::Unknown) { 0
579 setBottom(); 0
580 return true; 0
581 } ----
582 if (Ps != NewPs) { 0
583 Properties = NewPs; 0
584 Changed = true; 0
585 } ----
586 return Changed; 0
587 } ----
588 ----
589 // Add a property to the cell. This will force the cell to become a property- ----
590 // tracking cell. ----
591 bool LatticeCell::add(uint32_t Property) { 0
592 bool Changed = convertToProperty(); 0
593 uint32_t Ps = properties(); 0
594 if (Ps == (Ps & Property)) 0
595 return Changed; 0
596 Properties = Property & Ps; 0
597 return true; 0
598 } ----
599 ----
600 // Return the properties of the values in the cell. This is valid for any ----
601 // cell, and does not alter the cell itself. ----
602 uint32_t LatticeCell::properties() const { 0
603 if (isProperty()) 0
604 return Properties; 0
605 assert(!isTop() && "Should not call this for a top cell"); 0
606 if (isBottom()) 0
607 return ConstantProperties::Unknown; 0
608 ----
609 assert(size() > 0 && "Empty cell"); 0
610 uint32_t Ps = ConstantProperties::deduce(Values[0]); 0
611 for (unsigned i = 1; i < size(); ++i) { 0
612 if (Ps == ConstantProperties::Unknown) 0
613 break; 0
614 Ps &= ConstantProperties::deduce(Values[i]); 0
615 } ----
616 return Ps; 0
617 } ----

621 const TargetRegisterInfo &TRI) const { ----
622 for (auto &I : Map) 0
623 dbgs() << " " << printReg(I.first, &TRI) << " -> " << I.second << '\n'; 0

627 void MachineConstPropagator::visitPHI(const MachineInstr &PN) { 0
628 const MachineBasicBlock *MB = PN.getParent(); 0
629 unsigned MBN = MB->getNumber(); 0
630 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "Visiting FI(" << printMBBReference(*MB) << "): " << PN); 0
631 ----
632 const MachineOperand &MD = PN.getOperand(0); 0
633 RegisterSubReg DefR(MD); 0
634 assert(DefR.Reg.isVirtual()); 0
635 ----
636 bool Changed = false; 0
637 ----
638 // If the def has a sub-register, set the corresponding cell to "bottom". ----
639 if (DefR.SubReg) { 0
640 Bottomize: 0
641 const LatticeCell &T = Cells.get(DefR.Reg); 0
642 Changed = !T.isBottom(); 0
643 Cells.update(DefR.Reg, Bottom); 0
644 if (Changed) 0
645 visitUsesOf(DefR.Reg); 0
646 return; 0
647 } ----
648 ----
649 LatticeCell DefC = Cells.get(DefR.Reg); 0
650 ----
651 for (unsigned i = 1, n = PN.getNumOperands(); i < n; i += 2) { 0
652 const MachineBasicBlock *PB = PN.getOperand(i+1).getMBB(); 0
653 unsigned PBN = PB->getNumber(); 0
654 if (!EdgeExec.count(CFGEdge(PBN, MBN))) { 0
655 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << " edge " << printMBBReference(*PB) << "->" 0
656 << printMBBReference(*MB) << " not executable\n"); ----
657 continue; 0
658 } ----
659 const MachineOperand &SO = PN.getOperand(i); 0
660 RegisterSubReg UseR(SO); 0
661 // If the input is not a virtual register, we don't really know what ----
662 // value it holds. ----
663 if (!UseR.Reg.isVirtual()) 0
664 goto Bottomize; 0
665 // If there is no cell for an input register, it means top. ----
666 if (!Cells.has(UseR.Reg)) 0
667 continue; 0
668 ----
669 LatticeCell SrcC; 0
670 bool Eval = MCE.evaluate(UseR, Cells.get(UseR.Reg), SrcC); 0
671 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << " edge from " << printMBBReference(*PB) << ": " 0
672 << printReg(UseR.Reg, &MCE.TRI, UseR.SubReg) << SrcC ----
673 << '\n'); ----
674 Changed |= Eval ? DefC.meet(SrcC) 0
675 : DefC.setBottom(); 0
676 Cells.update(DefR.Reg, DefC); 0
677 if (DefC.isBottom()) 0
678 break; 0
679 } ----
680 if (Changed) 0
681 visitUsesOf(DefR.Reg); 0
682 } ----
683 ----
684 void MachineConstPropagator::visitNonBranch(const MachineInstr &MI) { 0
685 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "Visiting MI(" << printMBBReference(*MI.getParent()) 0
686 << "): " << MI); ----
687 CellMap Outputs; 0
688 bool Eval = MCE.evaluate(MI, Cells, Outputs); 0
689 LLVM_DEBUG({ 0
690 if (Eval) { ----
691 dbgs() << " outputs:"; ----
692 for (auto &I : Outputs) ----
693 dbgs() << ' ' << I.second; ----
694 dbgs() << '\n'; ----
695 } ----
696 }); ----
697 ----
698 // Update outputs. If the value was not computed, set all the ----
699 // def cells to bottom. ----
700 for (const MachineOperand &MO : MI.operands()) { 0
701 if (!MO.isReg() || !MO.isDef()) 0
702 continue; 0
703 RegisterSubReg DefR(MO); 0
704 // Only track virtual registers. ----
705 if (!DefR.Reg.isVirtual()) 0
706 continue; 0
707 bool Changed = false; 0
708 // If the evaluation failed, set cells for all output registers to bottom. ----
709 if (!Eval) { 0
710 const LatticeCell &T = Cells.get(DefR.Reg); 0
711 Changed = !T.isBottom(); 0
712 Cells.update(DefR.Reg, Bottom); 0
713 } else { ----
714 // Find the corresponding cell in the computed outputs. ----
715 // If it's not there, go on to the next def. ----
716 if (!Outputs.has(DefR.Reg)) 0
717 continue; 0
718 LatticeCell RC = Cells.get(DefR.Reg); 0
719 Changed = RC.meet(Outputs.get(DefR.Reg)); 0
720 Cells.update(DefR.Reg, RC); 0
721 } ----
722 if (Changed) 0
723 visitUsesOf(DefR.Reg); 0
724 } ----
725 } 0
726 ----
727 // Starting at a given branch, visit remaining branches in the block. ----
728 // Traverse over the subsequent branches for as long as the preceding one ----
729 // can fall through. Add all the possible targets to the flow work queue, ----
730 // including the potential fall-through to the layout-successor block. ----
731 void MachineConstPropagator::visitBranchesFrom(const MachineInstr &BrI) { 0
732 const MachineBasicBlock &B = *BrI.getParent(); 0
733 unsigned MBN = B.getNumber(); 0
734 MachineBasicBlock::const_iterator It = BrI.getIterator(); 0
735 MachineBasicBlock::const_iterator End = B.end(); 0
736 ----
737 SetVector Targets; 0
738 bool EvalOk = true, FallsThru = true; 0
739 while (It != End) { 0
740 const MachineInstr &MI = *It; 0
741 InstrExec.insert(&MI); 0
742 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "Visiting " << (EvalOk ? "BR" : "br") << "(" 0
743 << printMBBReference(B) << "): " << MI); ----
744 // Do not evaluate subsequent branches if the evaluation of any of the ----
745 // previous branches failed. Keep iterating over the branches only ----
746 // to mark them as executable. ----
747 EvalOk = EvalOk && MCE.evaluate(MI, Cells, Targets, FallsThru); 0
748 if (!EvalOk) 0
749 FallsThru = true; 0
750 if (!FallsThru) 0
751 break; 0
752 ++It; 0
753 } ----
754 ----
755 if (B.mayHaveInlineAsmBr()) 0
756 EvalOk = false; 0
757 ----
758 if (EvalOk) { 0
759 // Need to add all CFG successors that lead to EH landing pads. ----
760 // There won't be explicit branches to these blocks, but they must ----
761 // be processed. ----
762 for (const MachineBasicBlock *SB : B.successors()) { 0
763 if (SB->isEHPad()) 0
764 Targets.insert(SB); 0
765 } ----
766 if (FallsThru) { 0
767 const MachineFunction &MF = *B.getParent(); 0
768 MachineFunction::const_iterator BI = B.getIterator(); 0
769 MachineFunction::const_iterator Next = std::next(BI); 0
770 if (Next != MF.end()) 0
771 Targets.insert(&*Next); 0
772 } ----
773 } else { ----
774 // If the evaluation of the branches failed, make "Targets" to be the ----
775 // set of all successors of the block from the CFG. ----
776 // If the evaluation succeeded for all visited branches, then if the ----
777 // last one set "FallsThru", then add an edge to the layout successor ----
778 // to the targets. ----
779 Targets.clear(); 0
780 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << " failed to evaluate a branch...adding all CFG " 0
781 "successors\n"); ----
782 for (const MachineBasicBlock *SB : B.successors()) 0
783 Targets.insert(SB); 0
784 } ----
785 ----
786 for (const MachineBasicBlock *TB : Targets) { 0
787 unsigned TBN = TB->getNumber(); 0
788 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << " pushing edge " << printMBBReference(B) << " -> " 0
789 << printMBBReference(*TB) << "\n"); ----
790 FlowQ.push(CFGEdge(MBN, TBN)); 0
791 } ----
792 } 0
793 ----
794 void MachineConstPropagator::visitUsesOf(unsigned Reg) { 0
795 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "Visiting uses of " << printReg(Reg, &MCE.TRI) 0
796 << Cells.get(Reg) << '\n'); ----
797 for (MachineInstr &MI : MRI->use_nodbg_instructions(Reg)) { 0
798 // Do not process non-executable instructions. They can become exceutable ----
799 // later (via a flow-edge in the work queue). In such case, the instruc- ----
800 // tion will be visited at that time. ----
801 if (!InstrExec.count(&MI)) 0
802 continue; 0
803 if (MI.isPHI()) 0
804 visitPHI(MI); 0
805 else if (!MI.isBranch()) 0
806 visitNonBranch(MI); 0
807 else ----
808 visitBranchesFrom(MI); 0
809 } ----
810 } 0
811 ----
812 bool MachineConstPropagator::computeBlockSuccessors(const MachineBasicBlock *MB, 0
813 SetVector &Targets) { ----
814 Targets.clear(); 0
815 ----
816 MachineBasicBlock::const_iterator FirstBr = MB->end(); 0
817 for (const MachineInstr &MI : *MB) { 0
818 if (MI.getOpcode() == TargetOpcode::INLINEASM_BR) 0
819 return false; 0
820 if (MI.isDebugInstr()) 0
821 continue; 0
822 if (MI.isBranch()) { 0
823 FirstBr = MI.getIterator(); 0
824 break; 0
825 } ----
826 } ----
827 ----
828 MachineBasicBlock::const_iterator End = MB->end(); 0
829 ----
830 bool DoNext = true; 0
831 for (MachineBasicBlock::const_iterator I = FirstBr; I != End; ++I) { 0
832 const MachineInstr &MI = *I; 0
833 // Can there be debug instructions between branches? ----
834 if (MI.isDebugInstr()) 0
835 continue; 0
836 if (!InstrExec.count(&MI)) 0
837 continue; 0
838 bool Eval = MCE.evaluate(MI, Cells, Targets, DoNext); 0
839 if (!Eval) 0
840 return false; 0
841 if (!DoNext) 0
842 break; 0
843 } ----
844 // If the last branch could fall-through, add block's layout successor. ----
845 if (DoNext) { 0
846 MachineFunction::const_iterator BI = MB->getIterator(); 0
847 MachineFunction::const_iterator NextI = std::next(BI); 0
848 if (NextI != MB->getParent()->end()) 0
849 Targets.insert(&*NextI); 0
850 } ----
851 ----
852 // Add all the EH landing pads. ----
853 for (const MachineBasicBlock *SB : MB->successors()) 0
854 if (SB->isEHPad()) 0
855 Targets.insert(SB); 0
856 ----
857 return true; 0
858 } ----
859 ----
860 void MachineConstPropagator::removeCFGEdge(MachineBasicBlock *From, 0
861 MachineBasicBlock *To) { ----
862 // First, remove the CFG successor/predecessor information. ----
863 From->removeSuccessor(To); 0
864 // Remove all corresponding PHI operands in the To block. ----
865 for (MachineInstr &PN : To->phis()) { 0
866 // reg0 = PHI reg1, bb2, reg3, bb4, ... ----
867 int N = PN.getNumOperands() - 2; 0
868 while (N > 0) { 0
869 if (PN.getOperand(N + 1).getMBB() == From) { 0
870 PN.removeOperand(N + 1); 0
871 PN.removeOperand(N); 0
872 } ----
873 N -= 2; 0
874 } ----
875 } ----
876 } 0
877 ----
878 void MachineConstPropagator::propagate(MachineFunction &MF) { 0
879 MachineBasicBlock *Entry = GraphTraits::getEntryNode(&MF); 0
880 unsigned EntryNum = Entry->getNumber(); 0
881 ----
882 // Start with a fake edge, just to process the entry node. ----
883 FlowQ.push(CFGEdge(EntryNum, EntryNum)); 0
884 ----
885 while (!FlowQ.empty()) { 0
886 CFGEdge Edge = FlowQ.front(); 0
887 FlowQ.pop(); 0
888 ----
889 LLVM_DEBUG( 0
890 dbgs() << "Picked edge " ----
891 << printMBBReference(*MF.getBlockNumbered(Edge.first)) << "->" ----
892 << printMBBReference(*MF.getBlockNumbered(Edge.second)) << '\n'); ----
893 if (Edge.first != EntryNum) 0
894 if (EdgeExec.count(Edge)) 0
895 continue; 0
896 EdgeExec.insert(Edge); 0
897 MachineBasicBlock *SB = MF.getBlockNumbered(Edge.second); 0
898 ----
899 // Process the block in three stages: ----
900 // - visit all PHI nodes, ----
901 // - visit all non-branch instructions, ----
902 // - visit block branches. ----
903 MachineBasicBlock::const_iterator It = SB->begin(), End = SB->end(); 0
904 ----
905 // Visit PHI nodes in the successor block. ----
906 while (It != End && It->isPHI()) { 0
907 InstrExec.insert(&*It); 0
908 visitPHI(*It); 0
909 ++It; 0
910 } ----
911 ----
912 // If the successor block just became executable, visit all instructions. ----
913 // To see if this is the first time we're visiting it, check the first ----
914 // non-debug instruction to see if it is executable. ----
915 while (It != End && It->isDebugInstr()) 0
916 ++It; 0
917 assert(It == End || !It->isPHI()); 0
918 // If this block has been visited, go on to the next one. ----
919 if (It != End && InstrExec.count(&*It)) 0
920 continue; 0
921 // For now, scan all non-branch instructions. Branches require different ----
922 // processing. ----
923 while (It != End && !It->isBranch()) { 0
924 if (!It->isDebugInstr()) { 0
925 InstrExec.insert(&*It); 0
926 visitNonBranch(*It); 0
927 } ----
928 ++It; 0
929 } ----
930 ----
931 // Time to process the end of the block. This is different from ----
932 // processing regular (non-branch) instructions, because there can ----
933 // be multiple branches in a block, and they can cause the block to ----
934 // terminate early. ----
935 if (It != End) { 0
936 visitBranchesFrom(*It); 0
937 } else { ----
938 // If the block didn't have a branch, add all successor edges to the ----
939 // work queue. (There should really be only one successor in such case.) ----
940 unsigned SBN = SB->getNumber(); 0
941 for (const MachineBasicBlock *SSB : SB->successors()) 0
942 FlowQ.push(CFGEdge(SBN, SSB->getNumber())); 0
943 } ----
944 } // while (FlowQ) ----
945 ----
946 LLVM_DEBUG({ 0
947 dbgs() << "Cells after propagation:\n"; ----
948 Cells.print(dbgs(), MCE.TRI); ----
949 dbgs() << "Dead CFG edges:\n"; ----
950 for (const MachineBasicBlock &B : MF) { ----
951 unsigned BN = B.getNumber(); ----
952 for (const MachineBasicBlock *SB : B.successors()) { ----
953 unsigned SN = SB->getNumber(); ----
954 if (!EdgeExec.count(CFGEdge(BN, SN))) ----
955 dbgs() << " " << printMBBReference(B) << " -> " ----
956 << printMBBReference(*SB) << '\n'; ----
957 } ----
958 } ----
959 }); ----
960 } 0
961 ----
962 bool MachineConstPropagator::rewrite(MachineFunction &MF) { 0
963 bool Changed = false; 0
964 // Rewrite all instructions based on the collected cell information. ----
965 // ----
966 // Traverse the instructions in a post-order, so that rewriting an ----
967 // instruction can make changes "downstream" in terms of control-flow ----
968 // without affecting the rewriting process. (We should not change ----
969 // instructions that have not yet been visited by the rewriter.) ----
970 // The reason for this is that the rewriter can introduce new vregs, ----
971 // and replace uses of old vregs (which had corresponding cells ----
972 // computed during propagation) with these new vregs (which at this ----
973 // point would not have any cells, and would appear to be "top"). ----
974 // If an attempt was made to evaluate an instruction with a fresh ----
975 // "top" vreg, it would cause an error (abend) in the evaluator. ----
976 ----
977 // Collect the post-order-traversal block ordering. The subsequent ----
978 // traversal/rewrite will update block successors, so it's safer ----
979 // if the visiting order it computed ahead of time. ----
980 std::vector POT; 0
981 for (MachineBasicBlock *B : post_order(&MF)) 0
982 if (!B->empty()) 0
983 POT.push_back(B); 0
984 ----
985 for (MachineBasicBlock *B : POT) { 0
986 // Walk the block backwards (which usually begin with the branches). ----
987 // If any branch is rewritten, we may need to update the successor ----
988 // information for this block. Unless the block's successors can be ----
989 // precisely determined (which may not be the case for indirect ----
990 // branches), we cannot modify any branch. ----
991 ----
992 // Compute the successor information. ----
993 SetVector Targets; 0
994 bool HaveTargets = computeBlockSuccessors(B, Targets); 0
995 // Rewrite the executable instructions. Skip branches if we don't ----
996 // have block successor information. ----
997 for (MachineInstr &MI : llvm::reverse(*B)) { 0
998 if (InstrExec.count(&MI)) { 0
999 if (MI.isBranch() && !HaveTargets) 0
1000 continue; 0
1001 Changed |= MCE.rewrite(MI, Cells); 0
1002 } ----
1003 } ----
1004 // The rewriting could rewrite PHI nodes to non-PHI nodes, causing ----
1005 // regular instructions to appear in between PHI nodes. Bring all ----
1006 // the PHI nodes to the beginning of the block. ----
1007 for (auto I = B->begin(), E = B->end(); I != E; ++I) { 0
1008 if (I->isPHI()) 0
1009 continue; 0
1010 // I is not PHI. Find the next PHI node P. ----
1011 auto P = I; 0
1012 while (++P != E) 0
1013 if (P->isPHI()) 0
1014 break; 0
1015 // Not found. ----
1016 if (P == E) 0
1017 break; 0
1018 // Splice P right before I. ----
1019 B->splice(I, B, P); 0
1020 // Reset I to point at the just spliced PHI node. ----
1021 --I; 0
1022 } ----
1023 // Update the block successor information: remove unnecessary successors. ----
1024 if (HaveTargets) { 0
1025 SmallVector ToRemove; 0
1026 for (MachineBasicBlock *SB : B->successors()) { 0
1027 if (!Targets.count(SB)) 0
1028 ToRemove.push_back(const_cast(SB)); 0
1029 Targets.remove(SB); 0
1030 } ----
1031 for (MachineBasicBlock *MBB : ToRemove) 0
1032 removeCFGEdge(B, MBB); 0
1033 // If there are any blocks left in the computed targets, it means that ----
1034 // we think that the block could go somewhere, but the CFG does not. ----
1035 // This could legitimately happen in blocks that have non-returning ----
1036 // calls---we would think that the execution can continue, but the ----
1037 // CFG will not have a successor edge. ----
1038 } 0
1039 } 0
1040 // Need to do some final post-processing. ----
1041 // If a branch was not executable, it will not get rewritten, but should ----
1042 // be removed (or replaced with something equivalent to a A2_nop). We can't ----
1043 // erase instructions during rewriting, so this needs to be delayed until ----
1044 // now. ----
1045 for (MachineBasicBlock &B : MF) { 0
1046 for (MachineInstr &MI : llvm::make_early_inc_range(B)) 0
1047 if (MI.isBranch() && !InstrExec.count(&MI)) 0
1048 B.erase(&MI); 0
1049 } ----
1050 return Changed; 0
1051 } 0
1052 ----
1053 // This is the constant propagation algorithm as described by Wegman-Zadeck. ----
1054 // Most of the terminology comes from there. ----
1055 bool MachineConstPropagator::run(MachineFunction &MF) { 0
1056 LLVM_DEBUG(MF.print(dbgs() << "Starting MachineConstPropagator\n", nullptr)); 0
1057 ----
1058 MRI = &MF.getRegInfo(); 0
1059 ----
1060 Cells.clear(); 0
1061 EdgeExec.clear(); 0
1062 InstrExec.clear(); 0
1063 assert(FlowQ.empty()); 0
1064 ----
1065 propagate(MF); 0
1066 bool Changed = rewrite(MF); 0
1067 ----
1068 LLVM_DEBUG({ 0
1069 dbgs() << "End of MachineConstPropagator (Changed=" << Changed << ")\n"; ----
1070 if (Changed) ----
1071 MF.print(dbgs(), nullptr); ----
1072 }); ----
1073 return Changed; 0
1074 } ----
1075 ----
1076 // -------------------------------------------------------------------- ----
1077 // Machine const evaluator. ----
1078 ----
1079 bool MachineConstEvaluator::getCell(const RegisterSubReg &R, const CellMap &Inputs, 0
1080 LatticeCell &RC) { ----
1081 if (!R.Reg.isVirtual()) 0
1082 return false; 0
1083 const LatticeCell &L = Inputs.get(R.Reg); 0
1084 if (!R.SubReg) { 0
1085 RC = L; 0
1086 return !RC.isBottom(); 0
1087 } ----
1088 bool Eval = evaluate(R, L, RC); 0
1089 return Eval && !RC.isBottom(); 0
1090 } ----
1091 ----
1092 bool MachineConstEvaluator::constToInt(const Constant *C, 0
1093 APInt &Val) const { ----
1094 const ConstantInt *CI = dyn_cast(C); 0
1095 if (!CI) 0
1096 return false; 0
1097 Val = CI->getValue(); 0
1098 return true; 0
1099 } ----
1100 ----
1101 const ConstantInt *MachineConstEvaluator::intToConst(const APInt &Val) const { 0
1102 return ConstantInt::get(CX, Val); 0
1103 } ----
1104 ----
1105 bool MachineConstEvaluator::evaluateCMPrr(uint32_t Cmp, const RegisterSubReg &R1, 0
1106 const RegisterSubReg &R2, const CellMap &Inputs, bool &Result) { ----
1107 assert(Inputs.has(R1.Reg) && Inputs.has(R2.Reg)); 0
1108 LatticeCell LS1, LS2; 0
1109 if (!getCell(R1, Inputs, LS1) || !getCell(R2, Inputs, LS2)) 0
1110 return false; 0
1111 ----
1112 bool IsProp1 = LS1.isProperty(); 0
1113 bool IsProp2 = LS2.isProperty(); 0
1114 if (IsProp1) { 0
1115 uint32_t Prop1 = LS1.properties(); 0
1116 if (IsProp2) 0
1117 return evaluateCMPpp(Cmp, Prop1, LS2.properties(), Result); 0
1118 uint32_t NegCmp = Comparison::negate(Cmp); 0
1119 return evaluateCMPrp(NegCmp, R2, Prop1, Inputs, Result); 0
1120 } ----
1121 if (IsProp2) { 0
1122 uint32_t Prop2 = LS2.properties(); 0
1123 return evaluateCMPrp(Cmp, R1, Prop2, Inputs, Result); 0
1124 } ----
1125 ----
1126 APInt A; 0
1127 bool IsTrue = true, IsFalse = true; 0
1128 for (unsigned i = 0; i < LS2.size(); ++i) { 0
1129 bool Res; ----
1130 bool Computed = constToInt(LS2.Values[i], A) && 0
1131 evaluateCMPri(Cmp, R1, A, Inputs, Res); 0
1132 if (!Computed) 0
1133 return false; 0
1134 IsTrue &= Res; 0
1135 IsFalse &= !Res; 0
1136 } ----
1137 assert(!IsTrue || !IsFalse); 0
1138 // The actual logical value of the comparison is same as IsTrue. ----
1139 Result = IsTrue; 0
1140 // Return true if the result was proven to be true or proven to be false. ----
1141 return IsTrue || IsFalse; 0
1142 } 0
1143 ----
1144 bool MachineConstEvaluator::evaluateCMPri(uint32_t Cmp, const RegisterSubReg &R1, 0
1145 const APInt &A2, const CellMap &Inputs, bool &Result) { ----
1146 assert(Inputs.has(R1.Reg)); 0
1147 LatticeCell LS; 0
1148 if (!getCell(R1, Inputs, LS)) 0
1149 return false; 0
1150 if (LS.isProperty()) 0
1151 return evaluateCMPpi(Cmp, LS.properties(), A2, Result); 0
1152 ----
1153 APInt A; 0
1154 bool IsTrue = true, IsFalse = true; 0
1155 for (unsigned i = 0; i < LS.size(); ++i) { 0
1156 bool Res; ----
1157 bool Computed = constToInt(LS.Values[i], A) && 0
1158 evaluateCMPii(Cmp, A, A2, Res); 0
1159 if (!Computed) 0
1160 return false; 0
1161 IsTrue &= Res; 0
1162 IsFalse &= !Res; 0
1163 } ----
1164 assert(!IsTrue || !IsFalse); 0
1165 // The actual logical value of the comparison is same as IsTrue. ----
1166 Result = IsTrue; 0
1167 // Return true if the result was proven to be true or proven to be false. ----
1168 return IsTrue || IsFalse; 0
1169 } 0
1170 ----
1171 bool MachineConstEvaluator::evaluateCMPrp(uint32_t Cmp, const RegisterSubReg &R1, 0
1172 uint64_t Props2, const CellMap &Inputs, bool &Result) { ----
1173 assert(Inputs.has(R1.Reg)); 0
1174 LatticeCell LS; 0
1175 if (!getCell(R1, Inputs, LS)) 0
1176 return false; 0
1177 if (LS.isProperty()) 0
1178 return evaluateCMPpp(Cmp, LS.properties(), Props2, Result); 0
1179 ----
1180 APInt A; 0
1181 uint32_t NegCmp = Comparison::negate(Cmp); 0
1182 bool IsTrue = true, IsFalse = true; 0
1183 for (unsigned i = 0; i < LS.size(); ++i) { 0
1184 bool Res; ----
1185 bool Computed = constToInt(LS.Values[i], A) && 0
1186 evaluateCMPpi(NegCmp, Props2, A, Res); 0
1187 if (!Computed) 0
1188 return false; 0
1189 IsTrue &= Res; 0
1190 IsFalse &= !Res; 0
1191 } ----
1192 assert(!IsTrue || !IsFalse); 0
1193 Result = IsTrue; 0
1194 return IsTrue || IsFalse; 0
1195 } 0
1196 ----
1197 bool MachineConstEvaluator::evaluateCMPii(uint32_t Cmp, const APInt &A1, 0
1198 const APInt &A2, bool &Result) { ----
1199 // NE is a special kind of comparison (not composed of smaller properties). ----
1200 if (Cmp == Comparison::NE) { 0
1201 Result = !APInt::isSameValue(A1, A2); 0
1202 return true; 0
1203 } ----
1204 if (Cmp == Comparison::EQ) { 0
1205 Result = APInt::isSameValue(A1, A2); 0
1206 return true; 0
1207 } ----
1208 if (Cmp & Comparison::EQ) { 0
1209 if (APInt::isSameValue(A1, A2)) 0
1210 return (Result = true); 0
1211 } ----
1212 assert((Cmp & (Comparison::L | Comparison::G)) && "Malformed comparison"); 0
1213 Result = false; 0
1214 ----
1215 unsigned W1 = A1.getBitWidth(); 0
1216 unsigned W2 = A2.getBitWidth(); 0
1217 unsigned MaxW = (W1 >= W2) ? W1 : W2; 0
1218 if (Cmp & Comparison::U) { 0
1219 APInt Zx1 = A1.zext(MaxW); 0
1220 APInt Zx2 = A2.zext(MaxW); 0
1221 if (Cmp & Comparison::L) 0
1222 Result = Zx1.ult(Zx2); 0
1223 else if (Cmp & Comparison::G) 0
1224 Result = Zx2.ult(Zx1); 0
1225 return true; 0
1226 } 0
1227 ----
1228 // Signed comparison. ----
1229 APInt Sx1 = A1.sext(MaxW); 0
1230 APInt Sx2 = A2.sext(MaxW); 0
1231 if (Cmp & Comparison::L) 0
1232 Result = Sx1.slt(Sx2); 0
1233 else if (Cmp & Comparison::G) 0
1234 Result = Sx2.slt(Sx1); 0
1235 return true; 0
1236 } 0
1237 ----
1238 bool MachineConstEvaluator::evaluateCMPpi(uint32_t Cmp, uint32_t Props, 0
1239 const APInt &A2, bool &Result) { ----
1240 if (Props == ConstantProperties::Unknown) 0
1241 return false; 0
1242 ----
1243 // Should never see NaN here, but check for it for completeness. ----
1244 if (Props & ConstantProperties::NaN) 0
1245 return false; 0
1246 // Infinity could theoretically be compared to a number, but the ----
1247 // presence of infinity here would be very suspicious. If we don't ----
1248 // know for sure that the number is finite, bail out. ----
1249 if (!(Props & ConstantProperties::Finite)) 0
1250 return false; 0
1251 ----
1252 // Let X be a number that has properties Props. ----
1253 ----
1254 if (Cmp & Comparison::U) { 0
1255 // In case of unsigned comparisons, we can only compare against 0. ----
1256 if (A2 == 0) { 0
1257 // Any x!=0 will be considered >0 in an unsigned comparison. ----
1258 if (Props & ConstantProperties::Zero) 0
1259 Result = (Cmp & Comparison::EQ); 0
1260 else if (Props & ConstantProperties::NonZero) 0
1261 Result = (Cmp & Comparison::G) || (Cmp == Comparison::NE); 0
1262 else ----
1263 return false; 0
1264 return true; 0
1265 } ----
1266 // A2 is not zero. The only handled case is if X = 0. ----
1267 if (Props & ConstantProperties::Zero) { 0
1268 Result = (Cmp & Comparison::L) || (Cmp == Comparison::NE); 0
1269 return true; 0
1270 } ----
1271 return false; 0
1272 } ----
1273 ----
1274 // Signed comparisons are different. ----
1275 if (Props & ConstantProperties::Zero) { 0
1276 if (A2 == 0) 0
1277 Result = (Cmp & Comparison::EQ); 0
1278 else ----
1279 Result = (Cmp == Comparison::NE) || 0
1280 ((Cmp & Comparison::L) && !A2.isNegative()) || 0
1281 ((Cmp & Comparison::G) && A2.isNegative()); 0
1282 return true; 0
1283 } ----
1284 if (Props & ConstantProperties::PosOrZero) { 0
1285 // X >= 0 and !(A2 < 0) => cannot compare ----
1286 if (!A2.isNegative()) 0
1287 return false; 0
1288 // X >= 0 and A2 < 0 ----
1289 Result = (Cmp & Comparison::G) || (Cmp == Comparison::NE); 0
1290 return true; 0
1291 } ----
1292 if (Props & ConstantProperties::NegOrZero) { 0
1293 // X <= 0 and Src1 < 0 => cannot compare ----
1294 if (A2 == 0 || A2.isNegative()) 0
1295 return false; 0
1296 // X <= 0 and A2 > 0 ----
1297 Result = (Cmp & Comparison::L) || (Cmp == Comparison::NE); 0
1298 return true; 0
1299 } ----
1300 ----
1301 return false; 0
1302 } ----
1303 ----
1304 bool MachineConstEvaluator::evaluateCMPpp(uint32_t Cmp, uint32_t Props1, 0
1305 uint32_t Props2, bool &Result) { ----
1306 using P = ConstantProperties; ----
1307 ----
1308 if ((Props1 & P::NaN) && (Props2 & P::NaN)) 0
1309 return false; 0
1310 if (!(Props1 & P::Finite) || !(Props2 & P::Finite)) 0
1311 return false; 0
1312 ----
1313 bool Zero1 = (Props1 & P::Zero), Zero2 = (Props2 & P::Zero); 0
1314 bool NonZero1 = (Props1 & P::NonZero), NonZero2 = (Props2 & P::NonZero); 0
1315 if (Zero1 && Zero2) { 0
1316 Result = (Cmp & Comparison::EQ); 0
1317 return true; 0
1318 } ----
1319 if (Cmp == Comparison::NE) { 0
1320 if ((Zero1 && NonZero2) || (NonZero1 && Zero2)) 0
1321 return (Result = true); 0
1322 return false; 0
1323 } ----
1324 ----
1325 if (Cmp & Comparison::U) { 0
1326 // In unsigned comparisons, we can only compare against a known zero, ----
1327 // or a known non-zero. ----
1328 if (Zero1 && NonZero2) { 0
1329 Result = (Cmp & Comparison::L); 0
1330 return true; 0
1331 } ----
1332 if (NonZero1 && Zero2) { 0
1333 Result = (Cmp & Comparison::G); 0
1334 return true; 0
1335 } ----
1336 return false; 0
1337 } ----
1338 ----
1339 // Signed comparison. The comparison is not NE. ----
1340 bool Poz1 = (Props1 & P::PosOrZero), Poz2 = (Props2 & P::PosOrZero); 0
1341 bool Nez1 = (Props1 & P::NegOrZero), Nez2 = (Props2 & P::NegOrZero); 0
1342 if (Nez1 && Poz2) { 0
1343 if (NonZero1 || NonZero2) { 0
1344 Result = (Cmp & Comparison::L); 0
1345 return true; 0
1346 } ----
1347 // Either (or both) could be zero. Can only say that X <= Y. ----
1348 if ((Cmp & Comparison::EQ) && (Cmp & Comparison::L)) 0
1349 return (Result = true); 0
1350 } ----
1351 if (Poz1 && Nez2) { 0
1352 if (NonZero1 || NonZero2) { 0
1353 Result = (Cmp & Comparison::G); 0
1354 return true; 0
1355 } ----
1356 // Either (or both) could be zero. Can only say that X >= Y. ----
1357 if ((Cmp & Comparison::EQ) && (Cmp & Comparison::G)) 0
1358 return (Result = true); 0
1359 } ----
1360 ----
1361 return false; 0
1362 } ----
1363 ----
1364 bool MachineConstEvaluator::evaluateCOPY(const RegisterSubReg &R1, 0
1365 const CellMap &Inputs, LatticeCell &Result) { ----
1366 return getCell(R1, Inputs, Result); 0
1367 } ----
1368 ----
1369 bool MachineConstEvaluator::evaluateANDrr(const RegisterSubReg &R1, 0
1370 const RegisterSubReg &R2, const CellMap &Inputs, LatticeCell &Result) { ----
1371 assert(Inputs.has(R1.Reg) && Inputs.has(R2.Reg)); 0
1372 const LatticeCell &L1 = Inputs.get(R2.Reg); 0
1373 const LatticeCell &L2 = Inputs.get(R2.Reg); 0
1374 // If both sources are bottom, exit. Otherwise try to evaluate ANDri ----
1375 // with the non-bottom argument passed as the immediate. This is to ----
1376 // catch cases of ANDing with 0. ----
1377 if (L2.isBottom()) { 0
1378 if (L1.isBottom()) 0
1379 return false; 0
1380 return evaluateANDrr(R2, R1, Inputs, Result); 0
1381 } ----
1382 LatticeCell LS2; 0
1383 if (!evaluate(R2, L2, LS2)) 0
1384 return false; 0
1385 if (LS2.isBottom() || LS2.isProperty()) 0
1386 return false; 0
1387 ----
1388 APInt A; 0
1389 for (unsigned i = 0; i < LS2.size(); ++i) { 0
1390 LatticeCell RC; 0
1391 bool Eval = constToInt(LS2.Values[i], A) && 0
1392 evaluateANDri(R1, A, Inputs, RC); 0
1393 if (!Eval) 0
1394 return false; 0
1395 Result.meet(RC); 0
1396 } ----
1397 return !Result.isBottom(); 0
1398 } 0
1399 ----
1400 bool MachineConstEvaluator::evaluateANDri(const RegisterSubReg &R1, 0
1401 const APInt &A2, const CellMap &Inputs, LatticeCell &Result) { ----
1402 assert(Inputs.has(R1.Reg)); 0
1403 if (A2 == -1) 0
1404 return getCell(R1, Inputs, Result); 0
1405 if (A2 == 0) { 0
1406 LatticeCell RC; 0
1407 RC.add(intToConst(A2)); 0
1408 // Overwrite Result. ----
1409 Result = RC; 0
1410 return true; 0
1411 } ----
1412 LatticeCell LS1; 0
1413 if (!getCell(R1, Inputs, LS1)) 0
1414 return false; 0
1415 if (LS1.isBottom() || LS1.isProperty()) 0
1416 return false; 0
1417 ----
1418 APInt A, ResA; 0
1419 for (unsigned i = 0; i < LS1.size(); ++i) { 0
1420 bool Eval = constToInt(LS1.Values[i], A) && 0
1421 evaluateANDii(A, A2, ResA); 0
1422 if (!Eval) 0
1423 return false; 0
1424 const Constant *C = intToConst(ResA); 0
1425 Result.add(C); 0
1426 } ----
1427 return !Result.isBottom(); 0
1428 } 0
1429 ----
1430 bool MachineConstEvaluator::evaluateANDii(const APInt &A1, 0
1431 const APInt &A2, APInt &Result) { ----
1432 Result = A1 & A2; 0
1433 return true; 0
1434 } ----

1503 bool MachineConstEvaluator::evaluateXORrr(const RegisterSubReg &R1, 0
1504 const RegisterSubReg &R2, const CellMap &Inputs, LatticeCell &Result) { ----
1505 assert(Inputs.has(R1.Reg) && Inputs.has(R2.Reg)); 0

1507 if (!getCell(R1, Inputs, LS1) || !getCell(R2, Inputs, LS2)) 0
1508 return false; 0

1511 return !(Result = LS2).isBottom(); 0
1512 return false; 0

1514 if (LS2.isProperty()) { 0

1516 return !(Result = LS1).isBottom(); 0
1517 return false; 0
1518 } ----
1519 ----
1520 APInt A; 0
1521 for (unsigned i = 0; i < LS2.size(); ++i) { 0
1522 LatticeCell RC; 0
1523 bool Eval = constToInt(LS2.Values[i], A) && 0
1524 evaluateXORri(R1, A, Inputs, RC); 0

1526 return false; 0

1606 for (unsigned i = 0; i < LS1.size(); ++i) { 0
1607 bool Eval = constToInt(LS1.Values[i], A) && 0
1608 evaluateSEXTi(A, Width, Bits, XA); 0

1616 ----
1617 bool MachineConstEvaluator::evaluateSEXTi(const APInt &A1, unsigned Width, 0
1618 unsigned Bits, APInt &Result) { ----
1619 unsigned BW = A1.getBitWidth(); 0
1620 assert(Width >= Bits && BW >= Bits); 0
1621 // Special case to make things faster for smaller source widths. ----
1622 // Sign extension of 0 bits generates 0 as a result. This is consistent ----
1623 // with what the HW does. ----
1624 if (Bits == 0) { 0
1625 Result = APInt(Width, 0); 0
1626 return true; 0
1627 } ----
1628 // In C, shifts by 64 invoke undefined behavior: handle that case in APInt. ----
1629 if (BW <= 64 && Bits != 0) { 0
1630 int64_t V = A1.getSExtValue(); 0
1631 switch (Bits) { 0
1632 case 8: 0
1633 V = static_cast(V); 0
1634 break; 0
1635 case 16: 0
1636 V = static_cast(V); 0
1637 break; 0
1638 case 32: 0
1639 V = static_cast(V); 0
1640 break; 0
1641 default: 0
1642 // Shift left to lose all bits except lower "Bits" bits, then shift ----
1643 // the value back, replicating what was a sign bit after the first ----
1644 // shift. ----
1645 V = (V << (64-Bits)) >> (64-Bits); 0
1646 break; 0
1647 } ----
1648 // V is a 64-bit sign-extended value. Convert it to APInt of desired ----
1649 // width. ----
1650 Result = APInt(Width, V, true); 0
1651 return true; 0
1652 } ----
1653 // Slow case: the value doesn't fit in int64_t. ----
1654 if (Bits < BW) 0
1655 Result = A1.trunc(Bits).sext(Width); 0
1656 else // Bits == BW ----
1657 Result = A1.sext(Width); 0
1658 return true; 0
1659 } ----

1673 evaluateCLBi(A, Zeros, Ones, CA); 0
1674 if (!Eval) 0
1675 return false; 0
1676 const Constant *C = intToConst(CA); 0
1677 Result.add(C); 0
1678 } ----
1679 return true; 0
1680 } 0
1681 ----
1682 bool MachineConstEvaluator::evaluateCLBi(const APInt &A1, bool Zeros, 0
1683 bool Ones, APInt &Result) { ----
1684 unsigned BW = A1.getBitWidth(); 0
1685 if (!Zeros && !Ones) 0
1686 return false; 0
1687 unsigned Count = 0; 0
1688 if (Zeros && (Count == 0)) 0
1689 Count = A1.countl_zero(); 0
1690 if (Ones && (Count == 0)) 0
1691 Count = A1.countl_one(); 0
1692 Result = APInt(BW, static_cast(Count), false); 0
1693 return true; 0
1694 } ----

1730 ----
1731 bool MachineConstEvaluator::evaluateEXTRACTr(const RegisterSubReg &R1, 0
1732 unsigned Width, unsigned Bits, unsigned Offset, bool Signed, ----
1733 const CellMap &Inputs, LatticeCell &Result) { ----
1734 assert(Inputs.has(R1.Reg)); 0
1735 assert(Bits+Offset <= Width); 0
1736 LatticeCell LS1; 0
1737 if (!getCell(R1, Inputs, LS1)) 0
1738 return false; 0
1739 if (LS1.isBottom()) 0
1740 return false; 0
1741 if (LS1.isProperty()) { 0
1742 uint32_t Ps = LS1.properties(); 0
1743 if (Ps & ConstantProperties::Zero) { 0
1744 const Constant *C = intToConst(APInt(Width, 0, false)); 0
1745 Result.add(C); 0
1746 return true; 0
1747 } ----
1748 return false; 0
1749 } ----
1750 ----
1751 APInt A, CA; 0
1752 for (unsigned i = 0; i < LS1.size(); ++i) { 0
1753 bool Eval = constToInt(LS1.Values[i], A) && 0
1754 evaluateEXTRACTi(A, Bits, Offset, Signed, CA); 0
1755 if (!Eval) 0
1756 return false; 0
1757 const Constant *C = intToConst(CA); 0
1758 Result.add(C); 0
1759 } ----
1760 return true; 0
1761 } 0
1762 ----
1763 bool MachineConstEvaluator::evaluateEXTRACTi(const APInt &A1, unsigned Bits, 0
1764 unsigned Offset, bool Signed, APInt &Result) { ----
1765 unsigned BW = A1.getBitWidth(); 0
1766 assert(Bits+Offset <= BW); 0
1767 // Extracting 0 bits generates 0 as a result (as indicated by the HW people). ----
1768 if (Bits == 0) { 0
1769 Result = APInt(BW, 0); 0
1770 return true; 0
1771 } ----
1772 if (BW <= 64) { 0
1773 int64_t V = A1.getZExtValue(); 0
1774 V <<= (64-Bits-Offset); 0
1775 if (Signed) 0
1776 V >>= (64-Bits); 0
1777 else ----
1778 V = static_cast(V) >> (64-Bits); 0
1779 Result = APInt(BW, V, Signed); 0
1780 return true; 0
1781 } ----
1782 if (Signed) 0
1783 Result = A1.shl(BW-Bits-Offset).ashr(BW-Bits); 0
1784 else ----
1785 Result = A1.shl(BW-Bits-Offset).lshr(BW-Bits); 0
1786 return true; 0
1787 } ----
1788 ----
1789 bool MachineConstEvaluator::evaluateSplatr(const RegisterSubReg &R1, 0
1790 unsigned Bits, unsigned Count, const CellMap &Inputs, ----
1791 LatticeCell &Result) { ----
1792 assert(Inputs.has(R1.Reg)); 0
1793 LatticeCell LS1; 0
1794 if (!getCell(R1, Inputs, LS1)) 0
1795 return false; 0
1796 if (LS1.isBottom() || LS1.isProperty()) 0
1797 return false; 0
1798 ----
1799 APInt A, SA; 0
1800 for (unsigned i = 0; i < LS1.size(); ++i) { 0
1801 bool Eval = constToInt(LS1.Values[i], A) && 0
1802 evaluateSplati(A, Bits, Count, SA); 0
1803 if (!Eval) 0
1804 return false; 0
1805 const Constant *C = intToConst(SA); 0
1806 Result.add(C); 0
1807 } ----
1808 return true; 0
1809 } 0
1810 ----
1811 bool MachineConstEvaluator::evaluateSplati(const APInt &A1, unsigned Bits, 0
1812 unsigned Count, APInt &Result) { ----
1813 assert(Count > 0); 0
1814 unsigned BW = A1.getBitWidth(), SW = Count*Bits; 0
1815 APInt LoBits = (Bits < BW) ? A1.trunc(Bits) : A1.zext(Bits); 0
1816 if (Count > 1) 0
1817 LoBits = LoBits.zext(SW); 0
1818 ----
1819 APInt Res(SW, 0, false); 0
1820 for (unsigned i = 0; i < Count; ++i) { 0
1821 Res <<= Bits; 0
1822 Res |= LoBits; 0
1823 } ----
1824 Result = Res; 0
1825 return true; 0
1826 } 0

1923 ----
1924 bool HexagonConstEvaluator::evaluate(const MachineInstr &MI, 0
1925 const CellMap &Inputs, CellMap &Outputs) { ----
1926 if (MI.isCall()) 0
1927 return false; 0
1928 if (MI.getNumOperands() == 0 || !MI.getOperand(0).isReg()) 0
1929 return false; 0
1930 const MachineOperand &MD = MI.getOperand(0); 0
1931 if (!MD.isDef()) 0
1932 return false; 0
1933 ----
1934 unsigned Opc = MI.getOpcode(); 0
1935 RegisterSubReg DefR(MD); 0
1936 assert(!DefR.SubReg); 0
1937 if (!DefR.Reg.isVirtual()) 0
1938 return false; 0
1939 ----
1940 if (MI.isCopy()) { 0
1941 LatticeCell RC; 0
1942 RegisterSubReg SrcR(MI.getOperand(1)); 0
1943 bool Eval = evaluateCOPY(SrcR, Inputs, RC); 0
1944 if (!Eval) 0
1945 return false; 0
1946 Outputs.update(DefR.Reg, RC); 0
1947 return true; 0
1948 } ----
1949 if (MI.isRegSequence()) { 0
1950 unsigned Sub1 = MI.getOperand(2).getImm(); 0
1951 unsigned Sub2 = MI.getOperand(4).getImm(); 0
1952 const TargetRegisterClass &DefRC = *MRI->getRegClass(DefR.Reg); 0
1953 unsigned SubLo = HRI.getHexagonSubRegIndex(DefRC, Hexagon::ps_sub_lo); 0
1954 unsigned SubHi = HRI.getHexagonSubRegIndex(DefRC, Hexagon::ps_sub_hi); 0
1955 if (Sub1 != SubLo && Sub1 != SubHi) 0
1956 return false; 0
1957 if (Sub2 != SubLo && Sub2 != SubHi) 0
1958 return false; 0
1959 assert(Sub1 != Sub2); 0
1960 bool LoIs1 = (Sub1 == SubLo); 0
1961 const MachineOperand &OpLo = LoIs1 ? MI.getOperand(1) : MI.getOperand(3); 0
1962 const MachineOperand &OpHi = LoIs1 ? MI.getOperand(3) : MI.getOperand(1); 0
1963 LatticeCell RC; 0
1964 RegisterSubReg SrcRL(OpLo), SrcRH(OpHi); 0
1965 bool Eval = evaluateHexRSEQ32(SrcRL, SrcRH, Inputs, RC); 0
1966 if (!Eval) 0
1967 return false; 0
1968 Outputs.update(DefR.Reg, RC); 0
1969 return true; 0
1970 } ----
1971 if (MI.isCompare()) { 0
1972 bool Eval = evaluateHexCompare(MI, Inputs, Outputs); 0
1973 return Eval; 0
1974 } ----
1975 ----
1976 switch (Opc) { 0
1977 default: 0
1978 return false; 0
1979 case Hexagon::A2_tfrsi: 0
1980 case Hexagon::A2_tfrpi: ----
1981 case Hexagon::CONST32: ----
1982 case Hexagon::CONST64: ----
1983 { ----
1984 const MachineOperand &VO = MI.getOperand(1); 0
1985 // The operand of CONST32 can be a blockaddress, e.g. ----
1986 // %0 = CONST32 ----
1987 // Do this check for all instructions for safety. ----
1988 if (!VO.isImm()) 0
1989 return false; 0
1990 int64_t V = MI.getOperand(1).getImm(); 0
1991 unsigned W = getRegBitWidth(DefR.Reg); 0
1992 if (W != 32 && W != 64) 0
1993 return false; 0
1994 IntegerType *Ty = (W == 32) ? Type::getInt32Ty(CX) 0
1995 : Type::getInt64Ty(CX); 0
1996 const ConstantInt *CI = ConstantInt::get(Ty, V, true); 0
1997 LatticeCell RC = Outputs.get(DefR.Reg); 0
1998 RC.add(CI); 0
1999 Outputs.update(DefR.Reg, RC); 0
2000 break; 0
2001 } ----
2002 ----
2003 case Hexagon::PS_true: 0
2004 case Hexagon::PS_false: ----
2005 { ----
2006 LatticeCell RC = Outputs.get(DefR.Reg); 0
2007 bool NonZero = (Opc == Hexagon::PS_true); 0
2008 uint32_t P = NonZero ? ConstantProperties::NonZero 0
2009 : ConstantProperties::Zero; ----
2010 RC.add(P); 0
2011 Outputs.update(DefR.Reg, RC); 0
2012 break; 0
2013 } ----
2014 ----
2015 case Hexagon::A2_and: 0
2016 case Hexagon::A2_andir: ----
2017 case Hexagon::A2_andp: ----
2018 case Hexagon::A2_or: ----
2019 case Hexagon::A2_orir: ----
2020 case Hexagon::A2_orp: ----
2021 case Hexagon::A2_xor: ----
2022 case Hexagon::A2_xorp: ----
2023 { ----
2024 bool Eval = evaluateHexLogical(MI, Inputs, Outputs); 0
2025 if (!Eval) 0
2026 return false; 0
2027 break; 0
2028 } ----
2029 ----
2030 case Hexagon::A2_combineii: // combine(#s8Ext, #s8) 0
2031 case Hexagon::A4_combineii: // combine(#s8, #u6Ext) ----
2032 { ----
2033 if (!MI.getOperand(1).isImm() || !MI.getOperand(2).isImm()) 0
2034 return false; 0
2035 uint64_t Hi = MI.getOperand(1).getImm(); 0
2036 uint64_t Lo = MI.getOperand(2).getImm(); 0
2037 uint64_t Res = (Hi << 32) | (Lo & 0xFFFFFFFF); 0
2038 IntegerType *Ty = Type::getInt64Ty(CX); 0
2039 const ConstantInt *CI = ConstantInt::get(Ty, Res, false); 0
2040 LatticeCell RC = Outputs.get(DefR.Reg); 0
2041 RC.add(CI); 0
2042 Outputs.update(DefR.Reg, RC); 0
2043 break; 0
2044 } ----
2045 ----
2046 case Hexagon::S2_setbit_i: 0
2047 { ----
2048 int64_t B = MI.getOperand(2).getImm(); 0
2049 assert(B >=0 && B < 32); 0
2050 APInt A(32, (1ull << B), false); 0
2051 RegisterSubReg R(MI.getOperand(1)); 0
2052 LatticeCell RC = Outputs.get(DefR.Reg); 0
2053 bool Eval = evaluateORri(R, A, Inputs, RC); 0
2054 if (!Eval) 0
2055 return false; 0
2056 Outputs.update(DefR.Reg, RC); 0
2057 break; 0
2058 } 0
2059 ----
2060 case Hexagon::C2_mux: 0
2061 case Hexagon::C2_muxir: ----
2062 case Hexagon::C2_muxri: ----
2063 case Hexagon::C2_muxii: ----
2064 { ----
2065 bool Eval = evaluateHexCondMove(MI, Inputs, Outputs); 0
2066 if (!Eval) 0
2067 return false; 0
2068 break; 0
2069 } ----
2070 ----
2071 case Hexagon::A2_sxtb: 0
2072 case Hexagon::A2_sxth: ----
2073 case Hexagon::A2_sxtw: ----
2074 case Hexagon::A2_zxtb: ----
2075 case Hexagon::A2_zxth: ----
2076 { ----
2077 bool Eval = evaluateHexExt(MI, Inputs, Outputs); 0
2078 if (!Eval) 0
2079 return false; 0
2080 break; 0
2081 } ----
2082 ----
2083 case Hexagon::S2_ct0: 0
2084 case Hexagon::S2_ct0p: ----
2085 case Hexagon::S2_ct1: ----
2086 case Hexagon::S2_ct1p: ----
2087 { ----
2088 using namespace Hexagon; ----
2089 ----
2090 bool Ones = (Opc == S2_ct1) || (Opc == S2_ct1p); 0
2091 RegisterSubReg R1(MI.getOperand(1)); 0
2092 assert(Inputs.has(R1.Reg)); 0
2093 LatticeCell T; 0
2094 bool Eval = evaluateCTBr(R1, !Ones, Ones, Inputs, T); 0
2095 if (!Eval) 0
2096 return false; 0
2097 // All of these instructions return a 32-bit value. The evaluate ----
2098 // will generate the same type as the operand, so truncate the ----
2099 // result if necessary. ----
2100 APInt C; 0
2101 LatticeCell RC = Outputs.get(DefR.Reg); 0
2102 for (unsigned i = 0; i < T.size(); ++i) { 0
2103 const Constant *CI = T.Values[i]; 0
2104 if (constToInt(CI, C) && C.getBitWidth() > 32) 0
2105 CI = intToConst(C.trunc(32)); 0
2106 RC.add(CI); 0
2107 } ----
2108 Outputs.update(DefR.Reg, RC); 0
2109 break; 0
2110 } 0
2111 ----
2112 case Hexagon::S2_cl0: 0
2113 case Hexagon::S2_cl0p: ----
2114 case Hexagon::S2_cl1: ----
2115 case Hexagon::S2_cl1p: ----
2116 case Hexagon::S2_clb: ----
2117 case Hexagon::S2_clbp: ----
2118 { ----
2119 using namespace Hexagon; ----
2120 ----
2121 bool OnlyZeros = (Opc == S2_cl0) || (Opc == S2_cl0p); 0
2122 bool OnlyOnes = (Opc == S2_cl1) || (Opc == S2_cl1p); 0
2123 RegisterSubReg R1(MI.getOperand(1)); 0
2124 assert(Inputs.has(R1.Reg)); 0
2125 LatticeCell T; 0
2126 bool Eval = evaluateCLBr(R1, !OnlyOnes, !OnlyZeros, Inputs, T); 0
2127 if (!Eval) 0
2128 return false; 0
2129 // All of these instructions return a 32-bit value. The evaluate ----
2130 // will generate the same type as the operand, so truncate the ----
2131 // result if necessary. ----
2132 APInt C; 0
2133 LatticeCell RC = Outputs.get(DefR.Reg); 0
2134 for (unsigned i = 0; i < T.size(); ++i) { 0
2135 const Constant *CI = T.Values[i]; 0
2136 if (constToInt(CI, C) && C.getBitWidth() > 32) 0
2137 CI = intToConst(C.trunc(32)); 0
2138 RC.add(CI); 0
2139 } ----
2140 Outputs.update(DefR.Reg, RC); 0
2141 break; 0
2142 } 0
2143 ----
2144 case Hexagon::S4_extract: 0
2145 case Hexagon::S4_extractp: ----
2146 case Hexagon::S2_extractu: ----
2147 case Hexagon::S2_extractup: ----
2148 { ----
2149 bool Signed = (Opc == Hexagon::S4_extract) || 0
2150 (Opc == Hexagon::S4_extractp); ----
2151 RegisterSubReg R1(MI.getOperand(1)); 0
2152 unsigned BW = getRegBitWidth(R1.Reg); 0
2153 unsigned Bits = MI.getOperand(2).getImm(); 0
2154 unsigned Offset = MI.getOperand(3).getImm(); 0
2155 LatticeCell RC = Outputs.get(DefR.Reg); 0
2156 if (Offset >= BW) { 0
2157 APInt Zero(BW, 0, false); 0
2158 RC.add(intToConst(Zero)); 0
2159 break; 0
2160 } 0
2161 if (Offset+Bits > BW) { 0
2162 // If the requested bitfield extends beyond the most significant bit, ----
2163 // the extra bits are treated as 0s. To emulate this behavior, reduce ----
2164 // the number of requested bits, and make the extract unsigned. ----
2165 Bits = BW-Offset; 0
2166 Signed = false; 0
2167 } ----
2168 bool Eval = evaluateEXTRACTr(R1, BW, Bits, Offset, Signed, Inputs, RC); 0
2169 if (!Eval) 0
2170 return false; 0
2171 Outputs.update(DefR.Reg, RC); 0
2172 break; 0
2173 } ----
2174 ----
2175 case Hexagon::S2_vsplatrb: 0
2176 case Hexagon::S2_vsplatrh: ----
2177 // vabsh, vabsh:sat ----
2178 // vabsw, vabsw:sat ----
2179 // vconj:sat ----
2180 // vrndwh, vrndwh:sat ----
2181 // vsathb, vsathub, vsatwuh ----
2182 // vsxtbh, vsxthw ----
2183 // vtrunehb, vtrunohb ----
2184 // vzxtbh, vzxthw ----
2185 { ----
2186 bool Eval = evaluateHexVector1(MI, Inputs, Outputs); 0
2187 if (!Eval) 0
2188 return false; 0
2189 break; 0
2190 } ----
2191 ----
2192 // TODO: ----
2193 // A2_vaddh ----
2194 // A2_vaddhs ----
2195 // A2_vaddw ----
2196 // A2_vaddws ----
2197 } ----
2198 ----
2199 return true; 0
2200 } ----
2201 ----
2202 bool HexagonConstEvaluator::evaluate(const RegisterSubReg &R, 0
2203 const LatticeCell &Input, LatticeCell &Result) { ----
2204 if (!R.SubReg) { 0
2205 Result = Input; 0
2206 return true; 0
2207 } ----
2208 const TargetRegisterClass *RC = MRI->getRegClass(R.Reg); 0
2209 if (RC != &Hexagon::DoubleRegsRegClass) 0
2210 return false; 0
2211 if (R.SubReg != Hexagon::isub_lo && R.SubReg != Hexagon::isub_hi) 0
2212 return false; 0
2213 ----
2214 assert(!Input.isTop()); 0
2215 if (Input.isBottom()) 0
2216 return false; 0
2217 ----
2218 using P = ConstantProperties; ----
2219 ----
2220 if (Input.isProperty()) { 0
2221 uint32_t Ps = Input.properties(); 0
2222 if (Ps & (P::Zero|P::NaN)) { 0
2223 uint32_t Ns = (Ps & (P::Zero|P::NaN|P::SignProperties)); 0
2224 Result.add(Ns); 0
2225 return true; 0
2226 } ----
2227 if (R.SubReg == Hexagon::isub_hi) { 0
2228 uint32_t Ns = (Ps & P::SignProperties); 0
2229 Result.add(Ns); 0
2230 return true; 0
2231 } ----
2232 return false; 0
2233 } ----
2234 ----
2235 // The Input cell contains some known values. Pick the word corresponding ----
2236 // to the subregister. ----
2237 APInt A; 0
2238 for (unsigned i = 0; i < Input.size(); ++i) { 0
2239 const Constant *C = Input.Values[i]; 0
2240 if (!constToInt(C, A)) 0
2241 return false; 0
2242 if (!A.isIntN(64)) 0
2243 return false; 0
2244 uint64_t U = A.getZExtValue(); 0
2245 if (R.SubReg == Hexagon::isub_hi) 0
2246 U >>= 32; 0
2247 U &= 0xFFFFFFFFULL; 0
2248 uint32_t U32 = Lo_32(U); 0
2249 int32_t V32; ----
2250 memcpy(&V32, &U32, sizeof V32); 0
2251 IntegerType *Ty = Type::getInt32Ty(CX); 0
2252 const ConstantInt *C32 = ConstantInt::get(Ty, static_cast(V32)); 0
2253 Result.add(C32); 0
2254 } ----
2255 return true; 0
2256 } 0
2257 ----
2258 bool HexagonConstEvaluator::evaluate(const MachineInstr &BrI, 0
2259 const CellMap &Inputs, SetVector &Targets, ----
2260 bool &FallsThru) { ----
2261 // We need to evaluate one branch at a time. TII::analyzeBranch checks ----
2262 // all the branches in a basic block at once, so we cannot use it. ----
2263 unsigned Opc = BrI.getOpcode(); 0
2264 bool SimpleBranch = false; 0
2265 bool Negated = false; 0
2266 switch (Opc) { 0
2267 case Hexagon::J2_jumpf: 0
2268 case Hexagon::J2_jumpfnew: ----
2269 case Hexagon::J2_jumpfnewpt: ----
2270 Negated = true; 0
2271 [[fallthrough]]; ----
2272 case Hexagon::J2_jumpt: 0
2273 case Hexagon::J2_jumptnew: ----
2274 case Hexagon::J2_jumptnewpt: ----
2275 // Simple branch: if([!]Pn) jump ... ----
2276 // i.e. Op0 = predicate, Op1 = branch target. ----
2277 SimpleBranch = true; 0
2278 break; 0
2279 case Hexagon::J2_jump: 0
2280 Targets.insert(BrI.getOperand(0).getMBB()); 0
2281 FallsThru = false; 0
2282 return true; 0
2283 default: ----
2284 Undetermined: 0
2285 // If the branch is of unknown type, assume that all successors are ----
2286 // executable. ----
2287 FallsThru = !BrI.isUnconditionalBranch(); 0
2288 return false; 0
2289 } ----
2290 ----
2291 if (SimpleBranch) { 0
2292 const MachineOperand &MD = BrI.getOperand(0); 0
2293 RegisterSubReg PR(MD); 0
2294 // If the condition operand has a subregister, this is not something ----
2295 // we currently recognize. ----
2296 if (PR.SubReg) 0
2297 goto Undetermined; 0
2298 assert(Inputs.has(PR.Reg)); 0
2299 const LatticeCell &PredC = Inputs.get(PR.Reg); 0
2300 if (PredC.isBottom()) 0
2301 goto Undetermined; 0
2302 ----
2303 uint32_t Props = PredC.properties(); 0
2304 bool CTrue = false, CFalse = false; 0
2305 if (Props & ConstantProperties::Zero) 0
2306 CFalse = true; 0
2307 else if (Props & ConstantProperties::NonZero) 0
2308 CTrue = true; 0
2309 // If the condition is not known to be either, bail out. ----
2310 if (!CTrue && !CFalse) 0
2311 goto Undetermined; 0
2312 ----
2313 const MachineBasicBlock *BranchTarget = BrI.getOperand(1).getMBB(); 0
2314 ----
2315 FallsThru = false; 0
2316 if ((!Negated && CTrue) || (Negated && CFalse)) 0
2317 Targets.insert(BranchTarget); 0
2318 else if ((!Negated && CFalse) || (Negated && CTrue)) 0
2319 FallsThru = true; 0
2320 else ----
2321 goto Undetermined; 0
2322 } ----
2323 ----
2324 return true; 0
2325 } ----
2326 ----
2327 bool HexagonConstEvaluator::rewrite(MachineInstr &MI, const CellMap &Inputs) { 0
2328 if (MI.isBranch()) 0
2329 return rewriteHexBranch(MI, Inputs); 0
2330 ----
2331 unsigned Opc = MI.getOpcode(); 0
2332 switch (Opc) { 0
2333 default: 0
2334 break; 0
2335 case Hexagon::A2_tfrsi: 0
2336 case Hexagon::A2_tfrpi: ----
2337 case Hexagon::CONST32: ----
2338 case Hexagon::CONST64: ----
2339 case Hexagon::PS_true: ----
2340 case Hexagon::PS_false: ----
2341 return false; 0
2342 } ----
2343 ----
2344 unsigned NumOp = MI.getNumOperands(); 0
2345 if (NumOp == 0) 0
2346 return false; 0
2347 ----
2348 bool AllDefs, Changed; ----
2349 Changed = rewriteHexConstDefs(MI, Inputs, AllDefs); 0
2350 // If not all defs have been rewritten (i.e. the instruction defines ----
2351 // a register that is not compile-time constant), then try to rewrite ----
2352 // register operands that are known to be constant with immediates. ----
2353 if (!AllDefs) 0
2354 Changed |= rewriteHexConstUses(MI, Inputs); 0
2355 ----
2356 return Changed; 0
2357 } ----
2358 ----
2359 unsigned HexagonConstEvaluator::getRegBitWidth(unsigned Reg) const { 0
2360 const TargetRegisterClass *RC = MRI->getRegClass(Reg); 0
2361 if (Hexagon::IntRegsRegClass.hasSubClassEq(RC)) 0
2362 return 32; 0
2363 if (Hexagon::DoubleRegsRegClass.hasSubClassEq(RC)) 0
2364 return 64; 0
2365 if (Hexagon::PredRegsRegClass.hasSubClassEq(RC)) 0
2366 return 8; 0
2367 llvm_unreachable("Invalid register"); 0
2368 return 0; ----
2369 } ----
